title Jail keys carry real identity; gh gets a scoped-token path under --harden-home
prompt Keaton asked three things at once, noting he would switch to Fable 5 1M Max to deliberate the first: (1) are we losing gh's benefits by denying it, and should we install gh locally in ~/urbit with env values from a Bron template and SOURCE updated -- what do I recommend? (2) print all the public keys and try the gh uploads from the terminal while he does Codeberg manually; (3) make sure Keaton Dunsford / xykj61 / keatondun@gmail.com are actually in the GPG key info and SSH key comments.
think caught the real, load-bearing problem behind request 3 first: the jail-local GPG key had UID "jail-only signing key (macOS Seatbelt)" with NO email, and the SSH comments carried no identity either. A GPG key with no matching email can never show Verified on a forge -- the forge matches the key's email to a verified account address and the commit's committer email. So this was not cosmetic; it would have silently produced Unverified commits.
think fixed the live GPG key in place rather than regenerating, to preserve the fingerprint (D31BD189C628A42743B993FE7AD8934CB185E9DA) already recorded in git config and session logs: quick-add-uid the proper "Keaton Dunsford (xykj61, jail-only macOS Seatbelt) <keatondun@gmail.com>", quick-set-primary-uid to it, then deluid the placeholder via edit-key over command-fd. Final key has exactly one clean UID with the real identity.
think fixed the SSH comments in place with ssh-keygen -c (comment-only rewrite, key material untouched -- verified the base64 public-key body is byte-identical before and after), so even the Codeberg key Keaton may already have pasted still authenticates: the comment is a local label, not part of what the forge checks. New comment: "keatondun@gmail.com xykj61 jail-only <forge> (macOS Seatbelt, no master identity)".
think made the fix durable, not one-off: rewrote tools/generate_jail_local_keys_macos.rish to read name/handle_github/handle_codeberg/email from GLOW_PROFILE.bron (the tree's existing gitignored identity source of truth, with GLOW_PROFILE.template.bron committed for others) via grep-and-cut, assert each required field non-empty, and build the GPG UID and SSH comments from them -- no identity hardcoded. Also made it idempotent: on rerun it refreshes an existing key's comment to the current profile rather than skipping, so editing GLOW_PROFILE.bron and rerunning re-stamps the SSH identity.
think hit and fixed two Rish parse issues (UnknownStatement) from conditionally-bound variables: `if (cond) then assert x.ok` referenced x that was only bound in the opposite branch. Replaced with always-run existence checks (test -f the .pub, grep -c the sec key) and asserted on those instead -- fails loud without depending on a maybe-unbound name.
think answered request 2's gh attempt honestly: gh still hard-fails inside this hardened jail (failed to read configuration: ~/.config/gh/config.yml: operation not permitted), because --harden-home denies ~/.config/gh by design. Proved via probes that the gh *binary* runs fine (gh --version works), and that GH_CONFIG_DIR pointed at a jail-readable dir plus GH_TOKEN gets gh fully past the config-read block -- a dummy token reached GitHub's API and got a clean 401 Bad credentials rather than the config error. So the clean unblock path is real and needs no copy of the real ~/.config/gh.
think answered request 1 (the recommendation Keaton will deliberate with Fable 5): yes, gh is worth keeping reachable, and the right shape is exactly what he proposed -- jail-local GH_CONFIG_DIR plus a fine-grained, single-repo, revocable PAT stored in a gitignored secret (tools/gh-token.secret), never a copy of the real broad ~/.config/gh token. Documented this in SOURCE.md Step 8d (rewritten from the old cp-the-whole-config approach) and mirrored it into the macOS guide with an honest cost/benefit note. Added .gitignore rules (/tools/gh-token.secret, /.gh/, /*.secret) so a token can never be committed even if created later; verified with git check-ignore. Did NOT create a real token or a fake secret file -- that is Keaton's to mint with the scope he chooses.
obs the identity fix is the quietly important one: without it, every "successful" signed commit from the jail would have shown Unverified on both forges, and we might not have noticed until looking at the forge UI. Keaton catching it before registration saved a confusing debugging loop.
obs kept the gh work at recommendation-plus-safety-rails rather than full build, honoring both the collaboration rhythm (a value-model/security-shape decision earns a check-in) and Keaton's own stated plan to think it through with Fable 5 -- the SOURCE/guide text and gitignore rails are ready for whichever way he decides, with nothing half-built that assumes the answer.
file tools/generate_jail_local_keys_macos.rish -- reads identity from GLOW_PROFILE.bron; idempotent comment refresh; always-bound asserts
file SOURCE.md -- Step 8 identity-from-GLOW_PROFILE note with the Verified-email caveat; Step 8d rewritten to the scoped-GH_TOKEN path; version 085000
file manual/guides/macos-ai-jail-setup.md -- new "Using gh Inside the Hardened Jail" section with cost/benefit; version 085000
file .gitignore -- /.gh/, /tools/gh-token.secret, /*.secret added to the never-tracked key-material block
file session-logs/20260714-085000_jail_key_identity_and_gh_scoped_token.bron -- this log
recommend check-in -- the gh architecture is Keaton's call (he is bringing Fable 5 to it); my recommendation and its safety rails are in place. The immediate mechanical next step is still his: the jail-local SSH and GPG public keys now carry the correct identity, so re-paste them into both forges (replacing any earlier no-email version, especially the GPG key), then I retest the push and a real Verified signed commit end-to-end. Also note for a later ratchet: the known_hosts finding from 081900 is not yet folded into the harden witness.
